Question 7

library(leaflet)
met_avg2 <- met[,.(rh = mean(rh,na.rm=TRUE), lat = mean(lat), lon = mean(lon)),  by=c("USAFID")]
met_avg2 <- met_avg2[!is.na(rh)]
met_avg2 <- met_avg2[order(rh)]

# Generating a color palette
rh.pal <- colorNumeric(c('darkblue','goldenrod','red'), domain=met_avg2$rh)
rh.pal
function (x) 
{
    if (length(x) == 0 || all(is.na(x))) {
        return(pf(x))
    }
    if (is.null(rng)) 
        rng <- range(x, na.rm = TRUE)
    rescaled <- scales::rescale(x, from = rng)
    if (any(rescaled < 0 | rescaled > 1, na.rm = TRUE)) 
        warning("Some values were outside the color scale and will be treated as NA")
    if (reverse) {
        rescaled <- 1 - rescaled
    }
    pf(rescaled)
}

rhmap <- leaflet(met_avg2) %>% 
  # The looks of the Map
  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>% 
  # Some circles
  addCircles(
    lat = ~lat, lng=~lon,
                                                  # HERE IS OUR PAL!
    label = ~paste0(round(rh,2), ' C'), color = ~ rh.pal(rh),
    opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1, radius = 500
    ) %>%
  # And a pretty legend
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=rh.pal, values=met_avg2$rh,
          title='Relative Humidity', opacity=1) %>%
  addMarkers(data=tail(met_avg2,10), lng=~lon, lat=~lat)
rhmap

Based on our map the cities within the state of Florida had the highest relative humidity percentage. In general, a majority of the highest humidity cities are in the Southeast. Though two of the ten highest readings were in California, many of the lower relative humidity readings were in fact in California and other parts of the Southwest.

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

It is known by many that the humidity levels increase significantly the closer you are to the Earthâs equator and actually decreases the further north you travel. In an attempt to visually depict this relationship and test this association. Based on our plot we sort of have a tough time observing the hypothesized relationship stated previously. However, we do see a slight trend in that the relative humidity is generally higher on the east coast than on the west coast. Upon further research, this relationship does seem to be consistency with other knowledge.
